{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17632714","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17632714"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T17:43:26+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T17:43:26+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17434"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17434","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17434"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10124"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"70798"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10124","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10124"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17434"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56264"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"5326"},{"type":"tags","id":"5485"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"23724"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23804"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"70798","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/70798"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EQualitative research methods are essential tools in health and medical research, particularly when exploring complex social phenomena or human experiences.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the primary focus of phenomenological research design?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Analysing personal stories and narratives","Describing cultural patterns and behaviours","Understanding lived experiences and personal meanings","Investigating specific cases in detail","Developing new theories from systematic data analysis"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe primary focus of \u003Cstrong\u003Ephenomenological research\u003C/strong\u003E is understanding lived experiences and personal meanings of phenomena from the perspective of those who have experienced them. This approach is particularly valuable in healthcare research for understanding patient experiences of illness or treatment.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options represent other qualitative research designs:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAnalysing personal stories and narratives\u003C/strong\u003E describes narrative inquiry, which focuses on collecting and interpreting stories to understand personal experiences over time.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDescribing cultural patterns and behaviours\u003C/strong\u003E represents ethnographic research, which studies shared cultural patterns within specific groups or communities.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInvestigating specific cases in detail\u003C/strong\u003E characterises case study research, which examines specific instances or situations in depth.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDeveloping new theories from systematic data analysis\u003C/strong\u003E describes grounded theory methodology, which aims to generate new theories from systematic analysis of data.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPhenomenology helps researchers understand the essence of experiences through in-depth interviews and analysis of participants\u0027 descriptions, making it valuable for understanding patient perspectives in healthcare settings.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Qualitative research designs include phenomenology, ethnography, grounded theory, case studies, and narrative inquiry.","Phenomenology focuses on understanding lived experiences and personal meanings of a phenomenon.","Qualitative research methods are particularly useful for exploring complex social phenomena and generating new theories."],"references":["Ray, Sumantra, and others (eds), Oxford Handbook of Clinical and Healthcare Research, 1, Oxford Medical Handbooks (Oxford, 2016; online edn, Oxford Academic, 1 Mar. 2016), https://doi.org/10.1093/med/9780199608478.001.0001, accessed 12 Dec. 2024."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56264"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17434"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56264","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/56264"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-16T14:07:00+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-16T14:07:58+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10124"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"70798"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"